After changing his plea during today's hearing, Judge Timothy Pontius told the jury that they had heard Medvedevas' 'clear and voluntary confession of guilt'.

He told them: 'This is a distressing case and a tragic one. You are relieved of the burden of listening to that evidence.'

Medvedevas continues to deny inflicting the bite mark and the judge has yet to decide whether he was responsible for that particular wound.

Sentencing for his murder charge is set to take place next week but a date has not yet been fixed.

Defence barrister Sallie Bennett-Jenkins said: 'We are satisfied he has fully understood and comprehended the [legal] advice and equally, that he makes this admission of his own free will'.

